The Cathedral of the Violet Eclipse sits along western approaches from Midgaard toward Roc Road.
Close enough for city supply, far enough outside Watch circuits for deniable reliquary work.

Began as the Violet Arch Chapel-House, a Violet Compact era reliquary checkpoint.
Charter duties: threshold adjudication for relic caravans, ritual quarantine for unclassified artifacts, archive relay for oaths and confessions.
Violet pigments and amethyst lanterns indicated Compact jurisdiction, not occult significance.

Over decades it accumulated influence through institutional corruption. Families sought private rulings. Guild officers paid for accelerated attestation.
The same system that processed condemned persons as "arcane material" operated here.

The Silenced Vespers: reform clerks attempted to publish ledgers proving differential treatment (absolution for nobles, condemnation for laborers under identical evidence).
Bell-lines went silent. Outer doors sealed. Surviving clergy declared the institution "withdrawn into eclipse until judgment ripens."
No Midgaard magistrate challenged the withdrawal.

The Fivefold Occlusion litany encodes the corruption: color reveals rank, rank determines witness, witness determines memory, memory determines sentence, sentence determines who may be named.
The Eclipse doctrine teaches that truth requires institutional mediation to become legally real.
